#From the #1085 meta-list: "Doomsday with cards already exiled, they
#got shuffled into the deck". Cards in exile before the cast must
#stay there; the five picks become the library, the rest is exiled,
#and you lose half your life rounded up.
# https://github.com/WagicProject/wagic/issues/1085
[INIT]
FIRSTMAIN
[PLAYER1]
hand:doomsday
library:millstone,ornithopter,mox pearl,darksteel citadel,leaden myr
graveyard:walking corpse
exile:juggernaut
manapool:{B}{B}{B}
[PLAYER2]
[DO]
doomsday
millstone
ornithopter
mox pearl
darksteel citadel
leaden myr
goto firstmain
goto firstmain
goto firstmain
goto firstmain
goto secondmain
goto secondmain
[ASSERT]
SECONDMAIN
[PLAYER1]
library:millstone,ornithopter,mox pearl,darksteel citadel,leaden myr
graveyard:doomsday
exile:juggernaut,walking corpse
life:10
[PLAYER2]
[END]
#RE-MAPPED 2026-06-11 (post 23 engine rounds) - the pre-exile bug from the
#original report is GONE (juggernaut stays in exile; the 5 picks reach the
#library; life halves correctly). The sole dead leg: exile-the-rest.
#ROOT CAUSE FOUND - NESTED and! PARSE TRUNCATION: the and!( )! parse
#(parseBetween) is not nesting-aware, so the card's
#'and!( moveto(mylibrary) and!( <exile legs> )! )!' outer payload
#truncates at the INNER ')!' and the remainder is silently dropped (a
#'life:5' probe payload in the inner and! provably never fires).
#27 DATA LINES across borderline/macros/mtg carry nested and! - all
#truncating. ENGINE ROUND: make the and! extraction nesting-aware
#(match and!( ... )! with depth counting) in parseMagicLine.
#Attempted data workarounds, all dead-ended (kept for the map):
#  - spell-level 'all(*[-fresh]|...)' lines: spell LINE ORDER is not
#    execution order - the lords fired before the targeted chain, exiling
#    everything including the picks ([-fresh] is tick-fragile anyway).
#  - single-depth and! with direct lord payloads: ALord fired from an
#    and!-clone silently matches nothing (works as a spell line).
#  - becomes(kept) forever inside an and! payload: HANGS the suite.
#  - @movedto(this|mygraveyard) trigger for the exiles (Devils shape):
#    also hung in combination with the kept-tag payload.
#After the nesting-aware parse lands, the ORIGINAL data line should work
#as written (its inner transforms grants were never reached).
#UPDATE (same sitting): the depth-aware and! extraction LANDED (engine,
#suite 907+4/0) - the inner payload now parses and reaches its mover.
#Doomsday's remaining dead leg is ROOT CAUSE #2: the inner payload is
#transforms((,newability[all(...) moveto(exile)],...)) ON A LIBRARY
#CARD - granted abilities on out-of-play cards never tick (the
#transformer machinery strips/ignores grants whose bearer is not on the
#battlefield; same class as the watchers' pre-fix blink-hack). Next
#shape to try when reopened: put the exile legs somewhere that ticks -
#or extend the transformer to honor grants on the card it rides
#regardless of zone for oneshot payloads.
#UPDATE 2 (root-cause-2 dig, traces removed, sources pristine): the
#'transforms grants on library cards' theory was WRONG TOO - the real
#shape is stranger. Instrumented findings (all verified, then traces
#removed):
#  - Doomsday CASTS AND RESOLVES IMMEDIATELY (no cast-time target
#    collection); the <5> library/graveyard picker opens POST-resolution
#    (the general GTA+must-may fallback) and the 5 clicks feed it there.
#  - The and!-stash chain PARSES COMPLETELY post round-24: the inner
#    stash carries 'transforms(()) oneshot' and the transforms parse
#    site receives the full newability content via storedString
#    (verified at the parse site).
#  - BUT: AAMover::resolve NEVER RUNS in the entire test (entry trace,
#    verified present in the binary) - yet the picks END IN THE LIBRARY.
#    Something else moves them; the and!-chain (which lives on the
#    AAMover) is bypassed wholesale by whatever the post-resolution
#    picker flow uses to move cards. ATransformerInstant::resolve and
#    ATransformer::addToGame also never run.
#  - ALord::resolve runs only twice at INIT (rule cards).
#NEXT ENTRY: find what moves the picks in the post-resolution picker
#flow (gdb break MTGPlayerCards::putInZone with bt during the picks) -
#that mechanism needs to fire the line's and! chain, or the data needs
#a shape that rides the actual mechanism.
